          "title": "The worship — the LORD gave, the LORD took, blessed be His name",
          "body": "1:20-21 is the chapter's theological summit. *Then Job arose and tore his robe and shaved his head, and he fell to the ground and worshiped.* The grief is fully expressed — torn robe and shaved head are the standard Near Eastern mourning rites; Job does not stoicize his pain. But the grief becomes worship in the same motion. *Naked I came from my mother's womb, and naked I shall return there.* The chapter ends with the symmetry of birth and death bracketing all that lies between as a parenthesis. *The LORD gave and the LORD has taken away. Blessed be the name of the LORD.* Job uses the covenant name *YHWH* — twice naming Him as giver, once as taker, and yet blessing the same name. Verse 22 supplies the verdict: *through all this Job did not sin nor did he blame God.* The first round of the cosmic question is decided in Job's favor — disinterested worship exists, and the chapter has shown what it looks like."
